  <static seed="66" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/AddFractions20.pg">
    <statement><p>Add: <m>\displaystyle{\frac{2}{9} + \frac{1}{6}}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="10" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>{\frac{7}{18}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To add two fractions with different denominators, we first have to find a common denominator.</p>
<p>In this case, the least common multiple of <m>9</m> and <m>6</m> is <m>18</m>.</p>
<p>Look at the first fraction <m>\displaystyle{\frac{2}{9}}</m>. To change the denominator to <m>18</m>, we multiply <m>2</m> at both the top and bottom, and we have:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \begin{aligned}\frac{2}{9} \amp = \frac{2 \cdot 2}{9 \cdot 2}\\ \amp = \frac{4}{18}\end{aligned} }</m></p>
<p>Similarly, we change the second fraction<rsq/>s denominator to <m>18</m>:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \begin{aligned}\frac{1}{6} \amp = \frac{1 \cdot 3}{6 \cdot 3}\\ \amp = \frac{3}{18} \end{aligned}}</m></p>
<p>Now we can add those two fractions. The full process is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \frac{2}{9} + \frac{1}{6}
        \amp = \frac{4}{18} + \frac{3}{18} \\
        \amp = \frac{4 + 3}{18} \\
        \amp = \frac{7}{18}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The answer is  <m>\displaystyle{\frac{7}{18}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
